Mapping Census Data for Estimates of Households Receiving CalFresh in Marin County, CA¶

Written by: Greg Juarez

The poverty rate is 8.8% ±1.5% in Marin County, it is also known for being among the wealthiest counties in the United States. Located north of San Francisco, it has a population of 260,750; there are 2.5 persons per household. I thought it would be interesting to map data using information from the American Community Survey from the table S2201: FOOD STAMPS/SNAP for 5 year estimates for 2011 and 2014.

Background on the Data¶

The json file for the map was collected from the U.S. Census Bureau and is organized by zip code. The estimate of households on CalFresh was used for each data set with the goal of showing the increase of aid over time between 2011 and 2014. Sonoma County shares a zip code with Marin to the north but the goal is to visualize changes over time so it shouldn't be an issue.

The data is by household instead of by person; the maximum household size is 1,033 which turns into about 2,582 persons.

Pandas was used to clean up the data sets and a final data frame was created with the requirements for the map: zip codes, and the estimates of households on aid in each zip code.

In [1]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from pandas import DataFrame, Series
import folium
In [2]:
cf_2011_estimates = pd.read_csv('ACS2011 estimates/ACS_11_5YR_S2201_with_ann.csv')
cf_2011_estimates = cf_2011_estimates.rename(columns={'HC02_EST_VC01': '2011_CF'})
cf_2014_estimates = pd.read_csv('ACS 2014 estimates/ACS_14_5YR_S2201_with_ann.csv')
cf_2014_estimates = cf_2014_estimates.rename(columns={'HC02_EST_VC01': '2014_CF'})
zipcodes = DataFrame(cf_2014_estimates['GEO.id2'])
cf_2011 = DataFrame(cf_2011_estimates['2011_CF'])
cf_2014 = DataFrame(cf_2014_estimates['2014_CF'])
frames = [zipcodes,cf_2011,cf_2014]
results = pd.concat(frames, axis=1)
results = results[2:]

results['2011_CF'] = results['2011_CF'].astype(int)
results['2014_CF'] = results['2014_CF'].astype(int)

Setting up the Maps¶

Coordinates for each of the H&HS offices in Marin County were saved and placed on the map. Satelliete offices have a briefcase icon and main offices have a home icon.

In [4]:
hhsrw = [38.0209101,-122.5382071]
hhskern = [37.9604584,-122.5038321]
hhswm = [38.0691363,-122.811208]
hhsnv = [38.0946006,-122.5616718]

Each map shares the 2014 color map scale (threshold_scale = [0,208,416,624,832,1050]) for an easier comparison of changes over time; it measures the households on aid by color.

In [9]:
marinmap2011 = folium.Map(location=[37.9908788,-122.6014729], zoom_start=11)

folium.Marker(location=hhsrw, popup='H&HS 120',
              icon = folium.Icon(color='blue',icon='home')).add_to(marinmap2011)
folium.Marker(location=hhswm, popup='H&HS West Marin',
              icon = folium.Icon(color='blue',icon='home')).add_to(marinmap2011)

marinmap2011.geo_json(geo_str=open('marincountyzip2.json').read(),
             data=results,
             columns=['GEO.id2', '2011_CF'],
             key_on='id',
             fill_color='Set1',
             line_weight=1,
             legend_name='Households on CalFresh',
             threshold_scale = [0,208,416,624,832,1034],
                 )
In [6]:
marinmap2014 = folium.Map(location=[37.9908788,-122.6014729], zoom_start=11)

folium.Marker(location=hhsrw, popup='H&HS 120',
              icon = folium.Icon(color='blue',icon='home')).add_to(marinmap2014)
folium.Marker(location=hhskern, popup='H&HS Kerner',
              icon = folium.Icon(color='blue',icon='briefcase')).add_to(marinmap2014)
folium.Marker(location=hhswm, popup='H&HS West Marin',
              icon = folium.Icon(color='blue',icon='home')).add_to(marinmap2014)
folium.Marker(location=hhsnv, popup='H&HS Novato',
              icon = folium.Icon(color='blue',icon='briefcase')).add_to(marinmap2014)

marinmap2014.geo_json(geo_str=open('marincountyzip2.json').read(),
             data=results,
             columns=['GEO.id2', '2014_CF'],
             key_on='id',
             fill_color= 'Set1',

Impression¶

The percent change of households on aid from 2011 to 2015 is 50.91%; the map indicates this as different parts of the county had an increase of households on aid. Income inequality is present throughout the United States, and Marin County is no exception. It is widely known that California lags behind in participation rates for food stamps; seeing an increase of aid to the people that require help is a positive outcome for the community.
